For LinkedIn and cold outreach, Nick prefers a warm, personable tone over terse/punchy. His preferred structure:
- **Open:** "Hi <Name>, I applied for <role>, but wanted to reach out directly as well to say hi."
- **Middle:** the substance (for the job pivot: engineer with product experience making a deliberate move into product, wants a growing company with real purpose, works both sides of the fence and turns it into progress, betting on agentic AI, builds with it — one product launched, a second underway; keep product detail light).
- **Close:** "Would love to have a chat about the roles you have at <company>, and how someone with my skillset can help you and your team!"

He rejected an earlier terser, more clipped draft ("reaching out directly... Worth a chat?") as not warm enough.

**Why:** he wants to come across as friendly and someone worth talking to, not transactional.
**How to apply:** default to this warm open/close frame for his outreach; lead with a genuine hello, end with an enthusiastic, collaborative ask. Australian English, no em dashes, no colons in the message body (he dislikes both punctuation marks in his messages). Make existing experience explicit — "engineer with product experience moving fully into product", not "engineer moving into product" (the latter erases the product experience he already has). See [[feedback-nick-communication-rules]].
